===Etymology===
From {{bor|en|fr|Montréal}}; from {{m|fr|Mont Royal|gloss=[[Mount Royal]]}} {{gloss|{{compound|fr|mont|royal|nocat=1}}}}, after the nearby hill by Jacques Cartier. It is uncertain how {{m|fr|royal|Royal}} became ''-real''. A common explanation is that {{m|frm|real}} is the {{der|en|frm|-}} form of ''Royal'', but Cartier himself recorded ''le mont Royal'' when he named it. It may have perhaps been from the Italian G.B. Rasmusio's 1556 map translating the name to {{der|en|it|Monte Real}}.<ref>{{cite-web |website= Natural Resources Canada |title= Geographical Name - Island of Montreal |date= 22 August 2014 |url=http://www.nrcan.gc.ca/earth-sciences/geography/place-names/origins-geographical-names/9218 |accessdate=15 August 2015 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160803212245/https://www.nrcan.gc.ca/earth-sciences/geography/place-names/origins-geographical-names/9218 |archivedate=3 August 2016 |author= Jean Poirier |publicationdate= 1979 }}</ref>

